12.45pm Pakistan's bowlers bounced back early on the second morning, but it was familiar sightings for most of their batsmen.

Along with the WACA, the Gabba is one of the bounciest surfaces not only in Australia, but in the world. Pakistan simply failed to adjust to their surroundings against an attack that was never going to relent.

Awais: "If Sarfaraz scores a ton and Amir gets 50 and smith enforces follow on and Pakistan scores 350 in the second innnigs we might be able to avoid this upset!"

12.30pm A stunning day of Test cricket at the Gabba has set up Australia for a series lead. It's just day three but this game has moved along so quickly due to one crazy session that Australia may be thinking about taking a couple of extra days off. Steven Smith and Australia would have thought long and hard about whether they want to enforce the follow-on or not. Pakistan are still 332 runs behind. I know what I'd do.

The story of the first half of the second day was of two rookies: one who was nervous as a Test batsman, one who has appeared nerveless, writes Brydon Coverdale.

8.30pm The Gabba track quickened up on the second day, and 15 wickets tumbled, including eight Pakistan wickets. After Wahab and Amir collected four-wicket hauls to bowl Australia out for 429, Australia's quicks hit the deck harder under lights and razed Pakistan's batting line-up. The bowlers were ably supported by the cordon.

Aslam took two blows on the helmet off the bowling of Hazlewood, but battled for 100 balls, before tickling one down the leg side. Sarfraz then counterattacked briefly before stumps, but Pakistan are 97 for 8, still facing a deficit of 332 runs. Dan Bretting's report will tell you the full story of the day
